Promotional synergistic effect of Sn doping into a novel bimetallic Sn-W oxides/graphene catalyst for selective oxidation of alcohols using aqueous H2O2 without additives Cai Xu Lingling Zhang Yu An Xiaozhong Wang Gang Xu ⁎ Yingqi Chen Liyan Dai ⁎ Zhejiang Provincial Key Laboratory of Advanced Chemical Engineering Manufacture Technology, College of Chemical and Biological Engineering, Zhejiang University, Hangzhou, 310027, China Zhejiang Provincial Key Laboratory of Advanced Chemical Engineering Manufacture Technology College of Chemical and Biological Engineering Zhejiang University Hangzhou 310027 China ⁎ Corresponding authors. Graphical abstract A series of novel catalysts with bimetallic Sn-W oxides uniformly dispersed on reduced graphene oxide (denoted as Sn-W/RGO) were successfully prepared via a conventional one-pot hydrothermal method. Interestingly, it was found that the introduction of Sn could significantly improve the catalytic activities compared with single WO3/graphene catalyst for selective oxidation of alcohols using H2O2 without organic solvents and additives. Subsequently, the catalysts were characterized by FT-IR, XRD, Raman, FESEM, EDS, HRTEM, XPS and N2 adsorption-desorption to investigate the promotional synergistic effect of Sn among catalyst structure, surface properties and catalytic performance. The results revealed that the incorporation of Sn had induced the formation of hexagonal WO3 with dominant exposed (001) and (200) planes, meanwhile, doping Sn could dramatically increase the specific surface area, change the structural properties and enhance the interactions between Sn-W oxides and graphene, which were beneficial to the improvement of catalytic performance. Additionally, reaction parameters (temperature, time, oxidant dosage and catalyst amount) were also explored. Both aryl and alkyl alcohols exhibited high conversion and selectivity to corresponding target products over the catalyst. And delightedly, the robust catalyst could be reused for five times without significant loss in catalytic efficiency. This work demonstrates the promotional synergistic effect of Sn in a novel Sn-doped WO3/RGO catalyst and makes it a promising candidate in green oxidation of alcohols under mild reaction conditions. Keywords Sn-W oxides Graphene Synergistic effect Alcohols oxidation 1 Introduction Highly selective oxidation of alcohols to corresponding carbonyl compounds, emerging as one of the most essential chemical transformations in both academic and industrial research, because it produces valuable intermediates in pharmaceuticals, dyestuffs, agrochemicals, and fragrances industries [1–3]. Many homogeneous catalysts have been used to promote this oxidation process but inevitably bring some environmental problems, and the efficient recycling also remains a great challenge [4–8]. Hence, increasing efforts have been devoted in developing heterogeneous catalysts. Therein, noble metals (e.g., gold [9,10], palladium [11], ruthenium [12] and platinum [13]) exhibit excellent catalytic activities for this chemical transformation, but it is imperative to reduce their usage due to the low abundance and precious nature. Likewise, other non-noble transitional metals (e.g., cobalt [14], manganese [15], iron [16], bismuth [17] and copper [18]) have been explored for alcohols oxidation, but their efficiencies are usually lower in comparison with the noble metals based on substrate scope and catalytic performance, and non-green base additives (such as NaNO2, Na2CO3) are commonly added, served as active promoters to achieve higher selectivity to desirable products [19,20]. On the other hand, expensive and toxic oxidants such as chromium trioxide [21], tert-butyl hydroperoxide (TBHP) [22,23], and TEMPO [24] have been widely used in alcohols oxidation. However, from the environmental point of view, green oxidants such as O2 and H2O2 have proved to be more promising [25–27]. Particularly in aqueous solution, H2O2 is greatly attractive for releasing active oxidative species and producing water as the only by-product [28–30]. In this context, employing non-noble metals to fabricate efficient catalysts for alcohols oxidation with green oxidant is highly desirable. Traditionally, tungsten oxide (WO3) has been used in various oxidation reaction due to its attractive features, such as strong Lewis acidity, robust deprotonation capacity and highly hydrophilic properties [31–33]. Nevertheless, slow charge transfer and inadequate catalytic activities of pure WO3 confine it to a great extent in catalysis. To achieve better catalytic performances, it is suggested to turn from single metal to bimetallic composites, since bimetallic catalysts have proved to be more superior in catalytic activities compared to their monometallic counterparts [34,35]. In recent years, tin oxides have attracted considerable research interest in gas sensor, electrochromic devices and heterogeneous catalysis due to its appealing features, such as oxygen vacancies defects and variations in valence state [36,37]. More recently, Dai et al. prepared WO3/SnO2 catalyst for selective oxidation of 1, 2-benzenedimethanol with H2O2 and investigated the effect of calcination temperature of the support [38]. Kamata et al. synthesized heterogeneous W-Sn based catalyst for efficient oxidation of amines using H2O2 and achieved satisfying yield [39]. These reports have confirmed the fascinating potential of Sn-W oxides in the area of catalytic oxidation. Besides, considering that loss of active species and agglomeration of nanoparticles usually occur during the reaction process, it is urgent and meaningful to develop proper supports to immobilize metal components. Currently, graphene has attracted widespread attention in heterogeneous catalysis for its high surface area for dispersion of metal oxides and strong conductivity for electron transfer [26,40]. It was verified that when metal catalysts were anchored on graphene sheets, the composite displayed higher catalytic activity and longer durability due to the strong interaction between graphene and metals [41,42]. These remarkable performances make graphene an excellent support for metal oxides to construct high-efficiency catalysts. Therefore, the combination of binary Sn-W oxides anchored on graphene sheets is reasonably believed to possess much better catalytic performance. Herein, a series of novel bimetallic Sn-W oxides/graphene catalysts were firstly prepared via a conventional one-pot hydrothermal method. Then the catalytic activities for selective oxidation of alcohols using H2O2 without toxic solvents and additives were evaluated. And the effects of reaction parameters on catalytic activities over the bimetallic catalysts were also explored. Moreover, it was interesting to observe that introducing a certain amount of Sn species into the catalyst could dramatically enhance the catalytic performance for alcohols oxidation. Therefore, promotional synergistic effect of Sn was investigated in detail, and various characterizations were used to better understand the correlations between catalyst structure, surface properties and the enhanced catalytic activity resulting from the incorporation of Sn. 2 Experimental 2.1 Catalysts preparation All chemical reagents with analytical grade were used as received and without further purification. Graphene oxide (GO), the precursor of graphene, was synthesized based on a modified Hummer’s method from natural graphite powder [43]. Reagents and detailed preparation procedure of GO were presented in Supporting Information. Additionally, the Sn-doped WO3/RGO catalysts were prepared through a conventional one-pot hydrothermal reaction. Typically, the obtained GO was homogeneously dispersed in deionized water and sonicated for 2 h with the concentration of 0.5 mg/mL. Then, 5 mmol Na2WO4·2H2O, a certain molar amount of SnCl2·2H2O (the molar ratios of Sn to W = 0.1, 0.2, 0.3, 0.4, respectively) were dissolved in 50 ml above GO solution and kept stirring for 3 h. Afterwards, 37% hydrochloric acid solution was added dropwise to the above mixture under vigorous stirring until PH value of the solution was adjusted to 2, and then kept stirring for 3 h. Subsequently, the suspension was transferred into a 100 ml Teflon-lined autoclave to undergo a hydrothermal process at 140 ℃ for 14 h. After cooling to ambient temperature, the sample was collected and washed with deionized water and ethanol for several times, and then dried at 60 ℃ overnight in vacuum oven to give the bimetallic Sn-W oxides/graphene catalyst. For convenience, the resultant samples were labeled as ySn-W/RGO, where ‘y’ represents the Sn/W molar ratio. For comparison, WO3/RGO, SnO2/RGO were prepared through the same method above in the absence of Sn, W precursor, respectively. 2.2 Materials characterization Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FT-IR) spectra were recorded on a Nexus 670 spectrometer using KBr pellets in the range of 500–4000 cm−1. X-ray diffraction (XRD) patterns were collected on a PANalytical X’Pert PRO diffractometer using Cu Kα radiation (λ = 1.5406 Å). Raman spectra were tested by a ThermoFisher DXR SmartRaman spectrometer with the excitation wavelength of 532 nm. Field emission scanning electron microscopy (FESEM) images were taken on a Hitachi SU-70 microscope, and samples were analyzed by spreading them on a carbon tape. Energy dispersive X-ray spectrometer (EDS) connected with FESEM was used for elements analysis and elemental distribution mapping. Transmission electron microscopy (TEM) and high-resolution TEM (HRTEM) images were obtained from a FEI Tecnai G2 F20 S-TWIN microscope operated at 200 kV. X-ray photoelectron spectra (XPS) were measured on Thermo Scientific Escalab 250Xi spectrometer using Al Kα radiation at 20 kV, and the binding energies were calibrated with C 1 s peak at 284.6 eV. The surface area and pore volume of the catalysts were calculated by using BET and BJH methods from nitrogen adsorption-desorption isotherms at 77 K determined with a Micromeritics Belsorp-mini II (BEL Japan, Inc.). 2.3 Catalytic oxidation of alcohols The selective oxidation of benzyl alcohol using aqueous H2O2 without organic solvents and additives was chosen as the probe reaction to test the activities of as-prepared catalysts. Typically, benzyl alcohol (0.5 mmol), H2O2 (30 wt%, 0.6 mmol), deionized water (1 ml), catalyst (10 mg) were added sequentially into a sealed glass tube with vigorous magnetic stirring at 80 ℃ for 3 h. After the reaction, the solid catalyst was separated by centrifugation, and then washed with deionized water and ethanol thoroughly, followed by drying at 60 ℃ in vacuum oven overnight for reuse. The filtrate was extracted by ethyl acetate and then analyzed by GC (Agilent 6820, FID detector, 30 m hp-5 capillary column) with external standard method, and the products were identified through comparison with known standards. Additionally, to ensure the reproducibility of all activity tests, each result had been repeated at least three times and found to be within acceptable error ranges (±2.0%). 3 Results and discussion 3.1 Catalysts characterization 3.1.1 Structure and morphology characterization The FT-IR results of various Sn-W/RGO samples are depicted in Fig. 1 , for comparison, FT-IR spectra of GO and WO3/RGO are also presented. The band at around 3410 cm−1 was clearly found in all six spectra which could be ascribed to the stretching vibration mode of OH bond or physically adsorbed water. In the spectrum of GO in Fig. 1a, the characteristic absorption bands were distinctly observed at 1049 cm-1 ((CO)), 1224 cm-1 ((COC), 1621 cm-1 (CC) and 1736 cm-1 (CO), respectively [44,45]. The broad absorption bands in the range of 500–1000 cm−1 were assigned to stretching vibration of WO and SnO, but the difference was not quite obvious and thus XRD was used to further characterize the samples. Additionally, it should be noted that the peaks at 1224 cm−1 ((COC), 1736 cm−1 (CO) disappeared completely and the peaks at 3410 cm-1 ((OH)) became weak in these spectra of Sn-W/RGO, implying that the pristine GO has been partially reduced to RGO through the hydrothermal process and simultaneously the Sn-W/RGO composites have been successfully synthesized. The crystalline phase and structure of the obtained samples were characterized by XRD, with the results shown in Fig. 2 . A strong characteristic diffraction peak at around 9° of GO could be clearly observed, which was attributed to (002) plane with interplanar spacing of approximately 0.98 nm [26]. After hydrothermal process, the diffraction peaks of GO disappeared completely, but no obvious RGO peaks were found in the spectra of other samples due to its low content [46]. Additionally, the XRD patterns of WO3 shown in Fig. 2b could correspond to well-crystallized orthorhombic structure (JCPDS No. 20-1324). But with the addition of Sn from 0.1 to 0.4, the diffraction peaks of WO3 gradually changed. And notably, hexagonal WO3 (JCPDS No. 33-1387) emerged when the Sn/W molar ratio reached to 0.3, indicating that more Sn species had been incorporated into the lattice of WO3 crystallites and eventually caused this structure transformation. As regards these Sn-W/RGO catalysts (as shown in Fig. 2c, d, e, and f), the peak at 51.2° might ascribe to (211) plane of tetragonal SnO2 nanocrystals (JCPDS No. 41-1445) [38]. Moreover, the diffraction peaks of 0.3Sn-W/RGO were considerably broadened compared with those of WO3/RGO, suggesting that a smaller grain size was obtained, which also meant that doping Sn into the catalyst could enhance nucleation and inhibit size growth of the crystallites. The equivalent particle size of WO3 in WO3/RGO and 0.3Sn-W/RGO are 45.6 and 14.6 nm, respectively, calculated from the dominated (120) plane in Fig. 2b and (200) plane in Fig. 2e using Scherrer’s equation (Table 1 ). Raman spectroscopy was used to characterize the structure of obtained catalysts. Herein, it should be noted that the D band at around 1350 cm−1 and the G band at around 1595 cm−1 represent the disorder induced features caused by lattice defects and the first-order scattering of the E2g vibrational mode within sp2-hybridized graphene domains, respectively [26]. As shown in Table 1, the calculated ID/IG intensity ratios of WO3/RGO and 0.3Sn-W/RGO were 1.17 and 1.22, respectively. And both of them were larger than that of bare GO (0.73), demonstrating that unrepaired defects still remained after the removal of oxygen-containing functionalities by this hydrothermal synthesized process [47]. Notably, ID/IG ratio of 0.3Sn-W/RGO was slightly larger than that of WO3/RGO, indicating that the presence of Sn could decrease the graphitization degree and enhance the intrinsic disorder of graphene matrix. On the other hand, for WO3/RGO in Fig. 3 b, the peak at 270 and 320 cm−1 associated with the bending of dangling oxygen, δ ((OWO)), were clearly observed. Additionally, typical WO stretching vibration located at 717 cm-1 and the vibrational mode of the (OWO) stretching located at 810 cm−1 were also observed [48]. With the introduction of Sn, the dominant bands of 0.3Sn-W/RGO in Fig. 3c slightly shifted to low frequencies, which demonstrated the existence of strong interactions between Sn and W species. Besides, a new band at around 960 cm−1 appeared in spectrum of 0.3Sn-W/RGO, implying that the size of WO3 grains was quite small and in nanoscale, as reported by Pagnier et al. [49]. No obvious peaks of SnO were detected which might attribute to its weak Raman activity and low content, but the Raman analysis could further confirm the great impacts on WO3 and graphene arising from the introduction of Sn. FESEM and TEM were taken to investigate the morphological structure of the as-prepared catalysts. Fig. 4 a presents the FESEM image of WO3/RGO, it was clear that uniform WO3 nanoplates formed on the graphene sheets tightly with an average thickness of 60 nm. Nevertheless, for 0.3Sn-W/RGO in Fig. 4b, the particle size significantly decreased and the homogeneous nanoplates broke down to irregular shapes with the introduction of Sn. TEM images in Fig. 4c and d also suggested that doping Sn could remarkably refine grain size, which was in good accordance with the broadened peaks in XRD patterns and Raman analysis. The morphological changes might result from the penetration of Sn into WO3 lattice and the strong interactions between W and Sn. Additionally, the corresponding SAED pattern (Fig. 4e) confirmed that the 0.3Sn-W/RGO was close to polycrystalline structure in nature. Moreover, the lattice fringes could be observed clearly from the high-resolution TEM (HRTEM) images shown in Fig. 4f and g, indicating that these as-prepared samples were highly crystalline. The measured lattice fringe spacing of 0.335 nm in Fig. 4f exactly corresponds to the (120) plane of orthorhombic WO3 in WO3/RGO. In addition, Fig. 4g presents the lattice distances of 0.315 nm and 0.392 nm which are in good agreement with the dominant exposed (200) and (001) planes of hexagonal WO3 in 0.3Sn-W/RGO. The chemical composition and elemental distribution of 0.3Sn-W/RGO were also examined by using energy dispersive X-ray spectrometer (EDS), as presented in Fig. 4h and Fig. S6, only four elements of C, O, W and Sn were identified in the spectrum. These results evidently demonstrated that Sn species could play important roles in changing the catalyst structure and reducing the grain size, which associated with the better catalytic performance in alcohols oxidation. 3.1.2 XPS characterization XPS was perform to elucidate the surface components and chemical states of elements in GO, WO3/RGO and 0.3Sn-W/RGO samples. The overall XPS survey spectrum of 0.3Sn-W/RGO in Fig. 5 a confirmed the existence of elements C, O, W and Sn, meanwhile, no impurity element was found indicating the high purity of it. Additionally, the C 1 s spectrum of GO (Fig. 5b) could be divided into three peaks, including CC (284.4 eV) derived from graphitic matrix SP2 carbons, (CO) (286.5 eV) and CO (288.7 eV) originated from oxygenated groups attached to carbon atoms [26,50]. Besides, C 1 s spectra of WO3/RGO and 0.3Sn-W/RGO (Fig. 5b) were similar to that of GO, but intensity of the peaks related to oxygen-containing groups (such as (CO) and CO) were much weaker than those of GO and CC was the dominated peak, demonstrating that the hydrothermal reaction could remove oxygenated groups and make GO reduced to RGO. In the high resolution spectra of W 4f in WO3/RGO (Fig. 5c), two obvious peaks at 34.8 eV and 37.0 eV corresponding to two characteristic W 4f7/2 and W 4f5/2 peaks of W6+ in WO3/RGO were observed [51,52]. Notably, the binding energy values of W 4f7/2 and W 4f5/2 doublets in 0.3Sn-W/RGO were slightly larger than those of WO3/RGO, and both two peaks moved 0.2 eV to higher binding energy. Such a shift could be ascribed to the electron transfer and strong interactions between Sn and W species. In terms of XPS spectra of Sn 3d (Fig. 5d), it can be seen that the bands at 486.5 eV and 495.0 eV related to Sn 3d5/2 and Sn 3d3/2, respectively [53]. And the binding energies both shifted to a lower position compared to those of pure SnO2, implying that there were excess electrons around Sn and part of the low valence Sn species existed over 0.3Sn-W/RGO. Furthermore, the surface Sn/W molar ratio of 0.3Sn-W/RGO was lower than nominal ratio as shown in Table 1, demonstrating that a certain amount of Sn had penetrated into the WO3 lattice, which was well consistent with XRD analysis. And finally, based on these XPS results, it was reasonable to conclude that the introduction of Sn markedly changed the surface composition and enhanced the interactions between Sn-W oxides and graphene. 3.1.3 N2 adsorption-desorption analysis It is known that a larger surface area can offer more adsorption and reactive sites for catalytic reactions, leading to an improvement in catalytic activity. And thus the obtained samples were also measured by N2 adsorption-desorption, with the results shown in Table 1 and Fig. 6 . It is clear that WO3/RGO exhibits the typical type II N2 adsorption-desorption isotherm according to the IUPAC classification [26]. The obscure hysteresis and high adsorption at high P/P0 pressure indicated the formation of large mesopores and macropores, which might arise from the self-assembly of the interconnected nanosheets, these results were consistent well with the corresponding pore size distribution curve in Fig. 6b. However, with the introduction of Sn, the adsorption-desorption profiles of 0.3Sn-W/RGO were found to be different from those of WO3/RGO, displaying type IV isotherm with obvious H3 hysteresis loop based on the IUPAC classification [54]. And it implied the presence of slit-shape pores and small mesopores which were associated with the hierarchical structure, the pore size distribution centered at the range of 1–10 nm and the TEM image in Fig. 4d could also corroborate it. Correspondingly, the 0.3Sn-W/RGO has a BET surface area of 52.9 m2 g−1, which is several times higher than that of WO3/RGO (6.3 m2 g−1). Obviously verifying that doping Sn could greatly improve the specific surface area, which matched well with the small grain size obtained from XRD and TEM analysis. A larger surface area of 0.3Sn-W/RGO could provide more active sites for adsorption of the reactant molecules, making the catalytic oxidation process more efficient. 3.2 Catalytic oxidation of alcohols 3.2.1 Effect of reaction parameters The selective oxidation of benzyl alcohol (BzOH) to benzaldehyde (BzH) with H2O2 was carried out as a model reaction to estimate the activities of as-prepared catalysts. Firstly, a blank experiment without using catalysts was carried out, the listed result in Table S1 suggests that no significant BzOH conversion was achieved. Likewise, more detailed reaction parameters, such as reaction temperature, reaction time, H2O2 dosage and catalyst amount were also investigated to get the optimal reaction conditions, with results shown Table S1 and Fig. S1-4. It was found that reaction temperature and H2O2 dosage were key factors responsible for BzOH conversion and BzH selectivity. For example, the conversion increased significantly from 11.1% to 94.0% with the temperature increased from 40 ℃ to 80 ℃, which was attributed to the endothermic nature of this reaction and relatively high temperature could facilitate the reaction process. H2O2 dosage greatly affected the selectivity to desirable product and which reached a maximum of 94.3% when H2O2/BzOH molar ratio was only 1.2, excess oxidant would conversely decrease the selectivity. It is proposed that the reaction pathway of W-based catalytic system with H2O2 follows this: the main active component (W species) firstly reacts with H2O2 to form a peroxo complex, and then the complex further reacts with BzOH to give an intermediate, which finally gives BzH and regenerates the catalyst [55]. It also means the catalyst has little promotion in H2O2 self-decomposition into inactive oxygen species, the relatively low H2O2 dosage also corroborates it. And effect of reaction time on BzOH oxidation was also investigated with the results shown in Fig S3, prolonging the reaction time just achieved a little increase in BzOH conversion and inversely lowered the selectivity to BzH after the reaction ran for 3 h. Furthermore, Fig. S4 presents the influence of catalyst dosage used in this model reaction, and only 10 mg catalyst could obtain the maximum yield of BzH, indicating the high catalytic efficiency of this Sn-W/RGO catalyst. And thus the optimized reaction conditions for selective oxidation of benzyl alcohol with H2O2 in water were summarized as follows: H2O2/BzOH molar ratio was 1.2, the catalyst dosage was 10 mg and the reaction was performed at 80 ℃ for 3 h. Besides, with the optimized reaction conditions, both monometallic and a series of bimetallic Sn-W/RGO catalysts were tested for the selective oxidation of BzOH to BzH. Correlations between catalytic activity and Sn/W molar ratio were shown in Fig S5. It was found that the SnO2/RGO exhibited low BzOH conversion of 35.6%, but the WO3/RGO showed relatively high BzOH conversion of 78.5%, which indicated that WO3 were the main active components in the bimetallic catalysts. Interestingly, with the addition of Sn, much better catalytic activities were achieved over the Sn-W/RGO bimetallic catalysts. Both BzOH conversion and BzH selectivity maintained at around or above 90%, implying that the addition of Sn could significantly improve the catalytic performance and directly demonstrating the promotional synergistic effect of Sn. Among the Sn-W/RGO catalysts with different Sn/W molar ratios, 0.3Sn-W/RGO exhibited the optimal catalytic activity with the maximum yield to desirable product, and doping an excess of Sn would lead to a slight decrease in the yield of target product. Probably because overmuch Sn species dispersed on graphene sheets would occupy more sites for WO3 and then hinder the formation of peroxo complex with strong oxidizability, and thus decreasing the catalytic activity slightly. But overall, Sn species could act as an effective promoter among Sn-W/RGO to achieve higher catalytic performance compared with single WO3/RGO. Furthermore, comparison of this catalytic system with other catalytic systems for selective oxidation of benzyl alcohol to benzaldehyde was presented in Table 2 , and we could see the present catalysts exhibited remarkable catalytic activities in benzyl alcohol oxidation without using organic solvents and additives. 3.2.2 Catalyst reusability As a heterogeneous catalyst, stability and durability are of great importance in further industrial applications. Hence, recycling experiments over 0.3Sn-W/RGO for selective oxidation of benzyl alcohol with H2O2 was carried out. After the reaction, the catalyst was separated by simple centrifugation, then washed with ethanol thoroughly and dried overnight for next use. The results in Fig. 7 indicated that the heterogeneous catalyst could be successfully recycled for five times without significant loss in catalytic activities, both BzOH conversion and BzH selectivity maintained at above 90% during these recycled tests, demonstrating the highly excellent recyclability of this bimetallic catalyst. In addition, intensity of the diffraction peaks almost remained unchanged even after the catalyst was reused for five times as the XRD results shown in Fig. 8 . Moreover, inductively coupled plasma optical emission spectrometry (ICP-OES, Varian 730-ES) was used to detect the content of metal ions in the filtrate solution, the results suggested that no metal species were found under the detection limit of the apparatus. And thus these results indicated the extraordinary recyclability of this catalyst and revealed its application potential in future industrial scale. 3.2.3 General applicability In order to extend the general applicability of this bimetallic catalyst, the green and selective oxidation of various aromatic and aliphatic alcohols were investigated under the similar reaction conditions. And the results in Table 3 revealed that almost all the derivatives could favorably transform into corresponding aldehydes or ketones with high conversion and good selectivity. Taking benzyl alcohol for an example, bearing an electron-donating group (Entries 2 and 3) would increase the conversion to 96.3% and 98.3%, respectively. Nevertheless, the reaction rate and activity decreased slightly when adding electron-withdrawing groups on it (Entries 4 and 5). That might because the reduction of electron cloud density on aromatic rings caused by negative induction effect, which was detrimental to the improvement of catalytic activity in alcohols oxidation. With respect to the typical secondary aromatic alcohols (Entries 6–8), both high conversion and excellent selectivity were obtained under the moderate reaction conditions, and the selective oxidation of other primary aromatic alcohols (Entries 9 and 11) also proceeded efficiently. It was noteworthy that even cinnamyl alcohol (Entry 10) bearing activated double bonds worked well and afforded the target product in relatively high yield of 77.3%. Additionally, the present catalytic system was also applicable to the oxidation of secondary aliphatic alcohols (Entries 12–15), relatively appealing conversion and satisfying selectivity were achieved respectively by prolonging the reaction time. However, as regards the typical long-chain primary aliphatic alcohol (Entry 16), n-octanol presented relatively low yield to desired product though increasing the oxidant dosage, that might result from the effects of steric hindrance of its long-chain alkyl group and the absence of activation with the conjugated system [56]. Therefore, in general, a wide range of alcohols including aryl and alkyl alcohols were greatly suitable for this catalytic oxidation system, indicating the versatility of 0.3Sn-W/RGO catalyst for selective transformation of alcohols to corresponding carbonyl compounds with H2O2. 4 Conclusions In summary, a series of novel Sn-doped WO3/RGO catalysts were successfully prepared using a conventional one-pot hydrothermal method. Compared with single WO3/RGO catalyst, the bimetallic Sn-W/RGO catalysts (especially 0.3Sn-W/RGO) exhibited dramatic enhanced catalytic activities for selective oxidation of various alcohols to corresponding carbonyl compounds. The increased activities should be ascribed to the promotional synergistic effect of Sn and the strong interactions among the composites, which were confirmed by the above characterization results. Detailedly, the FT-IR, XRD, Raman and BET analysis revealed that the superior catalytic performance was attributed to better structure properties, such as higher surface area, preferential crystal configuration and strong interactions between Sn-W oxides and graphene. FESEM and TEM images verified that the incorporation of Sn could promote nucleation and dramatically decrease the grain size. XPS analysis further confirmed that the strong interactions among the catalysts and the great changes of chemical composition resulting from the introduction of Sn. All these advantages led to the outstanding improved catalytic performance of this bimetallic Sn-W/RGO catalyst. Besides, the Sn-promoted catalyst could catalyze the oxidation of both aryl and alkyl alcohols efficiently with H2O2 under moderate reactions conditions, which accorded well with the requirements of sustainable development and green chemistry. And its remarkable reusability also provided the great application potential in future industrial catalysis. coredata.dc:description: A series of novel catalysts with bimetallic Sn-W oxides uniformly dispersed on reduced graphene oxide (denoted as Sn-W/RGO) were successfully prepared via a conventional one-pot hydrothermal method. Interestingly, it was found that the introduction of Sn could significantly improve the catalytic activities compared with single WO3/graphene catalyst for selective oxidation of alcohols using H2O2 without organic solvents and additives. Subsequently, the catalysts were characterized by FT-IR, XRD, Raman, FESEM, EDS, HRTEM, XPS and N2 adsorption-desorption to investigate the promotional synergistic effect of Sn among catalyst structure, surface properties and catalytic performance. The results revealed that the incorporation of Sn had induced the formation of hexagonal WO3 with dominant exposed (001) and (200) planes, meanwhile, doping Sn could dramatically increase the specific surface area, change the structural properties and enhance the interactions between Sn-W oxides and graphene, which were beneficial to the improvement of catalytic performance. Additionally, reaction parameters (temperature, time, oxidant dosage and catalyst amount) were also explored. Both aryl and alkyl alcohols exhibited high conversion and selectivity to corresponding target products over the catalyst. And delightedly, the robust catalyst could be reused for five times without significant loss in catalytic efficiency. This work demonstrates the promotional synergistic effect of Sn in a novel Sn-doped WO3/RGO catalyst and makes it a promising candidate in green oxidation of alcohols under mild reaction conditions.
coredata.dc:title: Promotional synergistic effect of Sn doping into a novel bimetallic Sn-W oxides/graphene catalyst for selective oxidation of alcohols using aqueous H2O2 without additives
